              ffee8800::::<<aaddddrreessss>>%%<<aaddaapptteerr--nnaammee>>).

   EExxaammppllee
       llooccaallhhoosstt,,ffee8800::::aa0000::2277ffff::ffeeee00::11ffccff%%eennpp00ss33

   TTiipp
       When  possible,  use  a  logical DNS hostname instead of an ip address,
       particularly when configuring replica set members  or  sharded  cluster
       members.  The use of logical DNS hostnames avoids configuration changes
       due to ip address changes.

              WWAARRNNIINNGG::
                 Before binding to a non-localhost (e.g. publicly  accessible)
                 IP  address,  ensure you have secured your cluster from unau‐
                 thorized access. For a complete list of security  recommenda‐
                 tions,  see  /administration/security-checklist.  At minimum,
                 consider enabling authentication and hardening network infra‐
                 structure.

              For  more information about IP Binding, refer to the /core/secu‐
              rity-mongodb-configuration documentation.

              To bind to all IPv4 addresses, enter 00..00..00..00.

              To bind to all IPv4 and  IPv6  addresses,  enter  ::::,,00..00..00..00  or
              alternatively, use the nneett..bbiinnddIIppAAllll setting.

              NNOOTTEE::
                 ----bbiinndd__iipp and ----bbiinndd__iipp__aallll are mutually exclusive.  Specify‐
                 ing both options causes mmoonnggoodd to throw an error  and  termi‐
                 nate.

       ----bbiinndd__iipp__aallll
              New in version 3.6.

              If  specified,  the  mmoonnggoodd instance binds to all IPv4 addresses
              (i.e. 00..00..00..00). If mmoonnggoodd starts with _-_-_i_p_v_6, _-_-_b_i_n_d___i_p___a_l_l also
              binds to all IPv6 addresses (i.e. ::::).

              mmoonnggoodd  only  supports  IPv6  if started with _-_-_i_p_v_6. Specifying
              _-_-_b_i_n_d___i_p___a_l_l alone does not enable IPv6 support.

              WWAARRNNIINNGG::
                 Before binding to a non-localhost (e.g. publicly  accessible)
                 IP  address,  ensure you have secured your cluster from unau‐
                 thorized access. For a complete list of security  recommenda‐
                 tions,  see  /administration/security-checklist.  At minimum,
                 consider enabling authentication and hardening network infra‐
                 structure.

              For  more information about IP Binding, refer to the /core/secu‐
              rity-mongodb-configuration documentation.

              Alternatively, you can set the ----bbiinndd__iipp option to ::::,,00..00..00..00 to
              bind to all IP addresses.

              NNOOTTEE::
                 ----bbiinndd__iipp  and ----bbiinndd__iipp__aallll are mutually exclusive. That is,
                 you can specify one or the other, but not both.

       ----cclluusstteerrIIppSSoouurrcceeWWhhiitteelliisstt <<ssttrriinngg>>
              New in version 3.6.

              A list of IP  addresses/CIDR  (_C_l_a_s_s_l_e_s_s  _I_n_t_e_r_-_D_o_m_a_i_n  _R_o_u_t_i_n_g)
              ranges   against   which  the  _m_o_n_g_o_d  validates  authentication
              requests from other members of the replica set and, if part of a
              sharded  cluster, the mmoonnggooss instances. The _m_o_n_g_o_d verifies that
              the originating IP is either explicitly in the list  or  belongs
              to  a  CIDR range in the list. If the IP address is not present,
              the server does not authenticate the _m_o_n_g_o_d or mmoonnggooss.

              _-_-_c_l_u_s_t_e_r_I_p_S_o_u_r_c_e_W_h_i_t_e_l_i_s_t has no effect  on  a  _m_o_n_g_o_d  started
              without authentication.

              _-_-_c_l_u_s_t_e_r_I_p_S_o_u_r_c_e_W_h_i_t_e_l_i_s_t   accepts   multiple  comma-separated
              IPv4/6  addresses  or  Classless  Inter-Domain  Routing   (_C_I_D_R)
              ranges:

                 mongod --clusterIpSourceWhitelist 192.0.2.0/24,127.0.0.1,::1

              IIMMPPOORRTTAANNTT::
                 Ensure  _-_-_c_l_u_s_t_e_r_I_p_S_o_u_r_c_e_W_h_i_t_e_l_i_s_t includes the IP address _o_r
                 CIDR ranges that include the IP address of each  replica  set
                 member or mmoonnggooss in the deployment to ensure healthy communi‐
                 cation between cluster components.

       ----iippvv66 Enables IPv6 support. mmoonnggoodd disables IPv6 support by default.

              Setting _-_-_i_p_v_6 does _n_o_t direct the mmoonnggoodd to listen on any local
              IPv6  addresses or interfaces. To configure the mmoonnggoodd to listen
              on an IPv6 interface, you must either:

              · Configure _-_-_b_i_n_d___i_p with one or more IPv6 addresses  or  host‐
                names that resolve to IPv6 addresses, oorr

              · Set _-_-_b_i_n_d___i_p___a_l_l to ttrruuee.

       ----lliisstteennBBaacckklloogg <<nnuummbbeerr>>
              _D_e_f_a_u_l_t: Target system SSOOMMAAXXCCOONNNN constant

              New in version 3.6.

              The  maximum  number of connections that can exist in the listen
              queue.

              WWAARRNNIINNGG::
                 Consult your local system's documentation to  understand  the
                 limitations  and configuration requirements before using this
                 parameter.

              IIMMPPOORRTTAANNTT::
                 To prevent undefined  behavior,  specify  a  value  for  this
                 parameter between 11 and the local system SSOOMMAAXXCCOONNNN constant.

              The default value for the lliisstteennBBaacckklloogg parameter is set at com‐
              pile time to the target system SSOOMMAAXXCCOONNNN constant.  SSOOMMAAXXCCOONNNN is
              the  maximum  valid  value  that  is  documented for the _b_a_c_k_l_o_g
              parameter to the _l_i_s_t_e_n system call.

              Some systems may interpret SSOOMMAAXXCCOONNNN  symbolically,  and  others
              numerically.  The  actual _l_i_s_t_e_n _b_a_c_k_l_o_g applied in practice may
              differ from any numeric interpretation of the SSOOMMAAXXCCOONNNN constant
              or  argument  to ----lliisstteennBBaacckklloogg, and may also be constrained by
              system settings like nneett..ccoorree..ssoommaaxxccoonnnn on Linux.

              Passing a value for the lliisstteennBBaacckklloogg parameter that exceeds the
              SSOOMMAAXXCCOONNNN constant for the local system is, by the letter of the
              standards, undefined behavior. Higher  values  may  be  silently
              integer truncated, may be ignored, may cause unexpected resource
              consumption, or have other adverse consequences.

              On systems with workloads that exhibit  connection  spikes,  for
              which  it  is  empirically known that the local system can honor
              higher values for the _b_a_c_k_l_o_g parameter than the SSOOMMAAXXCCOONNNN  con‐
              stant, setting the lliisstteennBBaacckklloogg parameter to a higher value may
              reduce operation latency as observed by the client  by  reducing
              the number of connections which are forced into a backoff state.

       ----mmaaxxCCoonnnnss <<nnuummbbeerr>>
              The  maximum number of simultaneous connections that mmoonnggoodd will
              accept. This setting has no effect if it  is  higher  than  your
              operating   system's   configured  maximum  connection  tracking
              threshold.

              Do not assign too low of a value to this  option,  or  you  will
              encounter errors during normal application operation.

              NNOOTTEE::
                 Changed  in  version 2.6: MongoDB removed the upward limit on
                 the mmaaxxIInnccoommiinnggCCoonnnneeccttiioonnss setting.

       ----llooggppaatthh <<ppaatthh>>
              Sends all diagnostic logging information to a log  file  instead
              of  to  standard  output or to the host's syslog system. MongoDB
              creates the log file at the path you specify.

              By default, MongoDB will move any existing log file rather  than
              overwrite  it.  To  instead  append  to  the  log  file, set the
              _-_-_l_o_g_a_p_p_e_n_d option.

       ----ssyysslloogg
              Sends all logging output to the host's syslog system rather than
              to standard output or to a log file. , as with _-_-_l_o_g_p_a_t_h.

              The _-_-_s_y_s_l_o_g option is not supported on Windows.

              WWAARRNNIINNGG::
                 The  ssyysslloogg  daemon  generates timestamps when it logs a mes‐
                 sage, not when MongoDB issues the message. This can  lead  to
                 misleading  timestamps  for  log entries, especially when the
                 system is under heavy load. We recommend using the  _-_-_l_o_g_p_a_t_h
                 option for production systems to ensure accurate timestamps.

       ----ssyyssllooggFFaacciilliittyy <<ssttrriinngg>>
              _D_e_f_a_u_l_t: user

              Specifies  the facility level used when logging messages to sys‐
              log.  The value you specify must be supported by your  operating
              system's  implementation of syslog. To use this option, you must
              enable the _-_-_s_y_s_l_o_g option.

       ----llooggaappppeenndd
              Appends new entries to the end of the existing log file when the
              mmoonnggoodd  instance restarts. Without this option, _m_o_n_g_o_d will back
              up the existing log and create a new file.

       ----llooggRRoottaattee <<ssttrriinngg>>
              _D_e_f_a_u_l_t: rename

              New in version 3.0.0.

              Determines the behavior  for  the  llooggRRoottaattee  command.   Specify
              either rreennaammee or rreeooppeenn:

              · rreennaammee renames the log file.

              · rreeooppeenn  closes  and reopens the log file following the typical
                Linux/Unix log rotate behavior.  Use  rreeooppeenn  when  using  the
                Linux/Unix logrotate utility to avoid log loss.

                If you specify rreeooppeenn, you must also use _-_-_l_o_g_a_p_p_e_n_d.

       ----ttiimmeeSSttaammppFFoorrmmaatt <<ssttrriinngg>>
              _D_e_f_a_u_l_t: iso8601-local

              The  time  format for timestamps in log messages. Specify one of
              the following values:

                       ┌──────────────┬──────────────────────────────┐
                       │Value         │ Description                  │
                       ├──────────────┼──────────────────────────────┤
                       │ccttiimmee         │ Displays timestamps as WWeedd   │
                       │              │ DDeecc 3311 1188::1177::5544..881111.         │
