              _-_-_f_i_l_e_P_e_r_m_i_s_s_i_o_n_s applies only to Unix-based systems.

       ----ffoorrkk Enables a daemon mode that runs the mmoonnggoodd process in the  back‐
              ground.  By  default  mmoonnggoodd does not run as a daemon: typically
              you will run mmoonnggoodd as a daemon, either by using  _-_-_f_o_r_k  or  by
              using  a  controlling  process  that  handles  the daemonization
              process (e.g. as with uuppssttaarrtt and ssyysstteemmdd).

              The _-_-_f_o_r_k option is not supported on Windows.

       ----aauutthh Enables authorization  to  control  user's  access  to  database
              resources and operations. When authorization is enabled, MongoDB
              requires all clients to authenticate themselves first  in  order
              to determine the access for the client.

              Configure  users  via  the  mongo  shell. If no users exist, the
              localhost interface will continue to have access to the database
              until you create the first user.

              See Security for more information.

       ----nnooaauutthh
              Disables  authentication.  Currently  the  default.  Exists  for
              future compatibility and clarity.

       ----ttrraannssiittiioonnTTooAAuutthh
              New in version 3.4: Allows  the  mmoonnggoodd  to  accept  and  create
              authenticated  and  non-authenticated  connections  to  and from
              other _m_o_n_g_o_d and mmoonnggooss instances in the  deployment.  Used  for
              performing  rolling  transition of replica sets or sharded clus‐
              ters from a no-auth configuration  to  internal  authentication.
              Requires  specifying a internal authentication mechanism such as
              _-_-_k_e_y_F_i_l_e.

              For example, if using keyfiles for internal authentication,  the
              mmoonnggoodd  creates  an  authenticated connection with any _m_o_n_g_o_d or
              mmoonnggooss in the deployment using a matching keyfile. If the  secu‐
              rity  mechanisms do not match, the mmoonnggoodd utilizes a non-authen‐
              ticated connection instead.

              A mmoonnggoodd running with _-_-_t_r_a_n_s_i_t_i_o_n_T_o_A_u_t_h does not  enforce  user
              access  controls.  Users  may connect to your deployment without
              any access control checks and perform read, write, and  adminis‐
              trative operations.

              NNOOTTEE::
                 A  mmoonnggoodd  running  with  internal authentication and _w_i_t_h_o_u_t
                 _-_-_t_r_a_n_s_i_t_i_o_n_T_o_A_u_t_h requires clients  to  connect  using  user
                 access  controls.  Update  clients  to  connect to the mmoonnggoodd
                 using the appropriate user prior to restarting mmoonnggoodd without
                 _-_-_t_r_a_n_s_i_t_i_o_n_T_o_A_u_t_h.

       ----ccppuu  Forces  the  mmoonnggoodd process to report the percentage of CPU time
              in write lock, every four seconds.

       ----ssyyssiinnffoo
              Returns diagnostic system information and then exits. The infor‐
              mation provides the page size, the number of physical pages, and
              the number of available physical pages.

       ----nnoossccrriippttiinngg
