       ----sshhuuttddoowwnn
              The  _-_-_s_h_u_t_d_o_w_n  option cleanly and safely terminates the mmoonnggoodd
              process. When invoking mmoonnggoodd with this option you must set  the
              _-_-_d_b_p_a_t_h  option  either directly or by way of the configuration
              file and the _-_-_c_o_n_f_i_g option.

              The _-_-_s_h_u_t_d_o_w_n option is available only on Linux systems.

              For additional ways to shut down, see also terminate-mongod-pro‐
              cesses.

       ----rreeddaaccttCClliieennttLLooggDDaattaa
              New in version 3.4: Available in MongoDB Enterprise only.

              A  mmoonnggoodd running with _-_-_r_e_d_a_c_t_C_l_i_e_n_t_L_o_g_D_a_t_a redacts any message
              accompanying a given log event before logging. This prevents the
              mmoonnggoodd  from  writing  potentially  sensitive data stored on the
              database to the diagnostic log.  Metadata such as error or oper‐
              ation codes, line numbers, and source file names are still visi‐
              ble in the logs.

              Use  _-_-_r_e_d_a_c_t_C_l_i_e_n_t_L_o_g_D_a_t_a  in  conjunction   with   /core/secu‐
              rity-encryption-at-rest  and /core/security-transport-encryption
              to assist compliance with regulatory requirements.

              For example, a MongoDB deployment might store Personally Identi‐
              fiable  Information (PII) in one or more collections. The mmoonnggoodd
              logs events such as those related to CRUD  operations,  sharding
              metadata,  etc. It is possible that the mmoonnggoodd may expose PII as
              a part of  these  logging  operations.  A  mmoonnggoodd  running  with
              _-_-_r_e_d_a_c_t_C_l_i_e_n_t_L_o_g_D_a_t_a  removes  any  message  accompanying these
              events before being output to the log, effectively removing  the
              PII.

              Diagnostics  on  a mmoonnggoodd running with _-_-_r_e_d_a_c_t_C_l_i_e_n_t_L_o_g_D_a_t_a may
              be more difficult due to the lack  of  data  related  to  a  log
              event. See the process logging manual page for an example of the
              effect of _-_-_r_e_d_a_c_t_C_l_i_e_n_t_L_o_g_D_a_t_a on log output.

              You can enable or disable log  redaction  on  a  running  mmoonnggoodd
              using the sseettPPaarraammeetteerr database command.

                 db.adminCommand(
                   { setParameter: 1, redactClientLogData : true | false }
                 )

       ----nneettwwoorrkkMMeessssaaggeeCCoommpprreessssoorrss <<ssttrriinngg>>
              _D_e_f_a_u_l_t: snappy

              New in version 3.4.

              Specifies  the  default  compressor(s)  to use for communication
              between this mmoonnggoodd instance and:

              · other members of the deployment if the instance is part  of  a
                replica set or a sharded cluster

              · a mmoonnggoo shell

              · drivers that support the OOPP__CCOOMMPPRREESSSSEEDD message format.

              MongoDB supports the following compressors:

              · snappy

              · zlib (Available in MongoDB 3.6 or greater)

              IInn  vveerrssiioonnss  33..66 aanndd 44..00, _m_o_n_g_o_d and mmoonnggooss enable network com‐
              pression by default with ssnnaappppyy as the compressor.

              To disable network compression, set the value to ddiissaabblleedd.

              IIMMPPOORRTTAANNTT::
                 Messages are compressed when both parties enable network com‐
                 pression.  Otherwise, messages between the parties are uncom‐
                 pressed.

              If you specify multiple compressors, then the order in which you
              list the compressors matter as well as the communication initia‐
              tor. For example, if a mmoonnggoo shell specifies the following  net‐
              work   compressors   zzlliibb,,ssnnaappppyy   and   the   _m_o_n_g_o_d  specifies
              ssnnaappppyy,,zzlliibb, messages between mmoonnggoo shell and _m_o_n_g_o_d uses zzlliibb.

              If the parties do not share at least one common compressor, mes‐
              sages  between  the  parties are uncompressed. For example, if a
              mmoonnggoo shell specifies the network  compressor  zzlliibb  and  _m_o_n_g_o_d
              specifies  ssnnaappppyy,  messages  between mmoonnggoo shell and _m_o_n_g_o_d are
              not compressed.

       ----ttiimmeeZZoonneeIInnffoo <<ppaatthh>>
