       ----llddaappBBiinnddMMeetthhoodd <<ssttrriinngg>>
              _D_e_f_a_u_l_t: simple

              New in version 3.4: Available in MongoDB Enterprise only.

              The  method  mmoonnggoodd uses to authenticate to an LDAP server.  Use
              with _-_-_l_d_a_p_Q_u_e_r_y_U_s_e_r and _-_-_l_d_a_p_Q_u_e_r_y_P_a_s_s_w_o_r_d to connect  to  the
              LDAP server.

              _-_-_l_d_a_p_B_i_n_d_M_e_t_h_o_d supports the following values:

              · ssiimmppllee - mmoonnggoodd uses simple authentication.

              · ssaassll - mmoonnggoodd uses SASL protocol for authentication

              If you specify ssaassll, you can configure the available SASL mecha‐
              nisms using _-_-_l_d_a_p_B_i_n_d_S_A_S_L_M_e_c_h_a_n_i_s_m_s. mmoonnggoodd defaults  to  using
              DDIIGGEESSTT--MMDD55 mechanism.

       ----llddaappBBiinnddSSAASSLLMMeecchhaanniissmmss <<ssttrriinngg>>
              _D_e_f_a_u_l_t: DIGEST-MD5

              New in version 3.4: Available in MongoDB Enterprise only.

              A  comma-separated  list  of SASL mechanisms mmoonnggoodd can use when
              authenticating to the LDAP  server.  The  mmoonnggoodd  and  the  LDAP
              server  must agree on at least one mechanism. The mmoonnggoodd dynami‐
              cally loads any SASL mechanism libraries installed on  the  host
              machine at runtime.

              Install and configure the appropriate libraries for the selected
              SASL mechanism(s) on both the mmoonnggoodd host and  the  remote  LDAP
              server  host.  Your  operating  system  may include certain SASL
              libraries by default. Defer to the documentation associated with
              each  SASL mechanism for guidance on installation and configura‐
              tion.

              If using the GGSSSSAAPPII SASL mechanism for  use  with  security-ker‐
              beros, verify the following for the mmoonnggoodd host machine:

              LLiinnuuxx

                     · The KKRRBB55__CCLLIIEENNTT__KKTTNNAAMMEE environment variable resolves to
                       the name  of  the  client  keytab-files  for  the  host
                       machine.  For  more  on Kerberos environment variables,
                       please defer to the _K_e_r_b_e_r_o_s _d_o_c_u_m_e_n_t_a_t_i_o_n.

                     · The client keytab  includes  a  kerberos-user-principal
                       for  the  mmoonnggoodd  to  use  when  connecting to the LDAP
                       server and execute LDAP queries.

              WWiinnddoowwss
                     If connecting to an Active Directory server, the  Windows
                     Kerberos    configuration   automatically   generates   a
                     _T_i_c_k_e_t_-_G_r_a_n_t_i_n_g_-_T_i_c_k_e_t when the user logs onto  the  sys‐
                     tem. Set _-_-_l_d_a_p_B_i_n_d_W_i_t_h_O_S_D_e_f_a_u_l_t_s to ttrruuee to allow mmoonnggoodd
                     to use the generated credentials when connecting  to  the
                     Active Directory server and execute queries.

              Set _-_-_l_d_a_p_B_i_n_d_M_e_t_h_o_d to ssaassll to use this option.

              NNOOTTEE::
                 For  a complete list of SASL mechanisms see the _I_A_N_A _l_i_s_t_i_n_g.
                 Defer to the documentation for your LDAP or Active  Directory
                 service  for  identifying the SASL mechanisms compatible with
                 the service.

                 MongoDB is not a source of SASL mechanism libraries,  nor  is
                 the  MongoDB documentation a definitive source for installing
                 or configuring any given SASL  mechanism.  For  documentation
                 and  support,  defer  to the SASL mechanism library vendor or
                 owner.

                 For  more  information  on  SASL,  defer  to  the   following
                 resources:

                 · For Linux, please see the _C_y_r_u_s _S_A_S_L _d_o_c_u_m_e_n_t_a_t_i_o_n.

                 · For Windows, please see the _W_i_n_d_o_w_s _S_A_S_L _d_o_c_u_m_e_n_t_a_t_i_o_n.

       ----llddaappTTrraannssppoorrttSSeeccuurriittyy <<ssttrriinngg>>
              _D_e_f_a_u_l_t: tls

              New in version 3.4: Available in MongoDB Enterprise only.

              By  default,  mmoonnggoodd creates a TLS/SSL secured connection to the
              LDAP server.

              For Linux deployments, you must configure  the  appropriate  TLS
              Options in //eettcc//ooppeennllddaapp//llddaapp..ccoonnff file. Your operating system's
              package manager creates this file as part of the MongoDB  Enter‐
              prise installation, via the lliibbllddaapp dependency. See the documen‐
              tation for TTLLSS OOppttiioonnss in the _l_d_a_p_._c_o_n_f  _O_p_e_n_L_D_A_P  _d_o_c_u_m_e_n_t_a_t_i_o_n
              for more complete instructions.

              For Windows deployment, you must add the LDAP server CA certifi‐
              cates to the Windows certificate management tool. The exact name
              and  functionality  of  the tool may vary depending on operating
              system version. Please see the documentation for your version of
              Windows for more information on certificate management.

              Set  _-_-_l_d_a_p_T_r_a_n_s_p_o_r_t_S_e_c_u_r_i_t_y  to nnoonnee to disable TLS/SSL between
              mmoonnggoodd and the LDAP server.

              WWAARRNNIINNGG::
                 Setting _-_-_l_d_a_p_T_r_a_n_s_p_o_r_t_S_e_c_u_r_i_t_y to nnoonnee  transmits  plaintext
                 information  and  possibly credentials between mmoonnggoodd and the
                 LDAP server.

       ----llddaappTTiimmeeoouuttMMSS <<lloonngg>>
              _D_e_f_a_u_l_t: 10000

              New in version 3.4: Available in MongoDB Enterprise only.

              The amount of time in milliseconds mmoonnggoodd  should  wait  for  an
              LDAP server to respond to a request.

              Increasing  the  value of _-_-_l_d_a_p_T_i_m_e_o_u_t_M_S may prevent connection
              failure between the MongoDB server and the LDAP server,  if  the
              source  of  the  failure is a connection timeout. Decreasing the
              value of _-_-_l_d_a_p_T_i_m_e_o_u_t_M_S reduces the time MongoDB  waits  for  a
              response from the LDAP server.

              This  setting can be configured on a running mmoonnggoodd using sseettPPaa‐‐
              rraammeetteerr.

       ----llddaappUUsseerrTTooDDNNMMaappppiinngg <<ssttrriinngg>>
              New in version 3.4: Available in MongoDB Enterprise only.

              Maps the username provided to mmoonnggoodd  for  authentication  to  a
              LDAP   Distinguished   Name   (DN).   You   may   need   to  use
              _-_-_l_d_a_p_U_s_e_r_T_o_D_N_M_a_p_p_i_n_g to transform a username into an LDAP DN in
              the following scenarios:

              · Performing LDAP authentication with simple LDAP binding, where
                users authenticate to MongoDB with usernames that are not full
                LDAP DNs.

              · Using an _L_D_A_P _a_u_t_h_o_r_i_z_a_t_i_o_n _q_u_e_r_y _t_e_m_p_l_a_t_e that requires a DN.

              · Transforming  the usernames of clients authenticating to Mongo
                DB using different authentication mechanisms (e.g. x.509, ker‐
                beros) to a full LDAP DN for authorization.

              _-_-_l_d_a_p_U_s_e_r_T_o_D_N_M_a_p_p_i_n_g  expects a quote-enclosed JSON-string rep‐
              resenting an ordered array of documents. Each document  contains
              a  regular  expression  mmaattcchh and either a ssuubbssttiittuuttiioonn or llddaapp‐‐
              QQuueerryy template used for transforming the incoming username.

              Each document in the array has the following form:

                 {
                   match: "<regex>"
                   substitution: "<LDAP DN>" | ldapQuery: "<LDAP Query>"
                 }

               ┌─────────────┬─────────────────────┬─────────────────────────┐
               │Field        │ Description         │ Example                 │
               ├─────────────┼─────────────────────┼─────────────────────────┤
               │mmaattcchh        │ An  ECMAScript-for‐ │ ""((..++))EENNGGIINNEEEERRIINNGG""       │
               │             │ matted      regular │ ""((..++))DDBBAA""               │
               │             │ expression  (regex) │                         │
               │             │ to  match against a │                         │
               │             │ provided  username. │                         │
               │             │ Each      parenthe‐ │                         │
               │             │ sis-enclosed   sec‐ │                         │
               │             │ tion  represents  a │                         │
               │             │ regex capture group │                         │
               │             │ used  by  ssuubbssttiittuu‐‐ │                         │
               │             │ ttiioonn or llddaappQQuueerryy.  │                         │
               └─────────────┴─────────────────────┴─────────────────────────┘

               │ssuubbssttiittuuttiioonn │ An   LDAP   distin‐ │ ""ccnn=={{00}},,oouu==eennggii‐‐        │
               │             │ guished  name  (DN) │ nneeeerriinngg,,   ddcc==eexxaamm‐‐     │
               │             │ formatting template │ ppllee,,ddcc==ccoomm""             │
               │             │ that  converts  the │                         │
               │             │ authentication name │                         │
               │             │ matched   by    the │                         │
               │             │ mmaattcchh  regex into a │                         │
               │             │ LDAP   DN.     Each │                         │
               │             │ curly               │                         │
               │             │ bracket-enclosed    │                         │
               │             │ numeric   value  is │                         │
               │             │ replaced   by   the │                         │
               │             │ corresponding _r_e_g_e_x │                         │
               │             │ _c_a_p_t_u_r_e       _g_r_o_u_p │                         │
               │             │ extracted  from the │                         │
               │             │ authentication      │                         │
               │             │ username   via  the │                         │
               │             │ mmaattcchh regex.        │                         │
               │             │                     │                         │
               │             │ The result  of  the │                         │
               │             │ substitution   must │                         │
               │             │ be    an    _R_F_C_4_5_1_4 │                         │
               │             │ escaped string.     │                         │
               ├─────────────┼─────────────────────┼─────────────────────────┤
               │llddaappQQuueerryy    │ A  LDAP  query for‐ │ ""oouu==eennggiinneeeerr‐‐           │
               │             │ matting    template │ iinngg,,ddcc==eexxaammppllee,,         │
               │             │ that   inserts  the │ ddcc==ccoomm????oonnee??((uusseerr=={{00}}))"" │
               │             │ authentication name │                         │
               │             │ matched    by   the │                         │
               │             │ mmaattcchh regex into an │                         │
               │             │ LDAP    query   URI │                         │
               │             │ encoded  respecting │                         │
               │             │ RFC4515         and │                         │
               │             │ RFC4516. Each curly │                         │
               │             │ bracket-enclosed    │                         │
               │             │ numeric  value   is │                         │
               │             │ replaced   by   the │                         │
               │             │ corresponding _r_e_g_e_x │                         │
               │             │ _c_a_p_t_u_r_e       _g_r_o_u_p │                         │
               │             │ extracted from  the │                         │
               │             │ authentication      │                         │
               │             │ username  via   the │                         │
               │             │ mmaattcchh   expression. │                         │
               │             │ mmoonnggoodd executes the │                         │
               │             │ query  against  the │                         │
               │             │ LDAP   server    to │                         │
               │             │ retrieve  the  LDAP │                         │
               │             │ DN for the  authen‐ │                         │
               │             │ ticated  user. mmoonn‐‐ │                         │
               │             │ ggoodd        requires │                         │
               │             │ exactly         one │                         │
               │             │ returned result for │                         │
               │             │ the  transformation │                         │
               │             │ to  be  successful, │                         │
               │             │ or   mmoonnggoodd   skips │                         │
               │             │ this    transforma‐ │                         │
               │             │ tion.               │                         │
               └─────────────┴─────────────────────┴─────────────────────────┘

              NNOOTTEE::
                 An explanation of  _R_F_C_4_5_1_4, _R_F_C_4_5_1_5, _R_F_C_4_5_1_6, or LDAP queries
                 is  out of scope for the MongoDB Documentation. Please review
                 the RFC directly or use your preferred LDAP resource.

              For each document in the array, you must use either ssuubbssttiittuuttiioonn
              or llddaappQQuueerryy. You _c_a_n_n_o_t specify both in the same document.

              When  performing  authentication  or authorization, mmoonnggoodd steps
              through each document in the array in the given order,  checking
              the  authentication  username  against  the  mmaattcchh filter.  If a
              match is found, mmoonnggoodd applies the transformation and  uses  the
              output  for  authenticating  the user. mmoonnggoodd does not check the
              remaining documents in the array.

              If the given document does not match the provided authentication
              name,  or  the  transformation  described by the document fails,
              mmoonnggoodd continues through the list of  documents  to  find  addi‐
              tional  matches. If no matches are found in any document, mmoonnggoodd
              returns an error.

   EExxaammppllee
       The following shows two transformation documents.  The  first  document
       matches  against  any  string  ending in @@EENNGGIINNEEEERRIINNGG, placing anything
       preceeding the suffix into a regex capture group. The  second  document
       matches  against any string ending in @@DDBBAA, placing anything preceeding
       the suffix into a regex capture group.

       IIMMPPOORRTTAANNTT::
          You must pass the array to _-_-_l_d_a_p_U_s_e_r_T_o_D_N_M_a_p_p_i_n_g as a string.

          "[
             {
                match: "(.+)@ENGINEERING.EXAMPLE.COM",
                substitution: "cn={0},ou=engineering,dc=example,dc=com"
             },
             {
                match: "(.+)@DBA.EXAMPLE.COM",
                ldapQuery: "ou=dba,dc=example,dc=com??one?(user={0})"

             }

          ]"

       A user with username aalliiccee@@EENNGGIINNEEEERRIINNGG..EEXXAAMMPPLLEE..CCOOMM  matches  the  first
       document.  The regex capture group {{00}} corresponds to the string aalliiccee.
       The  resulting  output  is  the  DN   ""ccnn==aalliiccee,,oouu==eennggiinneeeerriinngg,,ddcc==eexxaamm‐‐
       ppllee,,ddcc==ccoomm"".

       A  user  with username bboobb@@DDBBAA..EEXXAAMMPPLLEE..CCOOMM matches the second document.
       The regex capture group {{00}} corresponds to the string bboobb.  The result‐
       ing      output      is     the     LDAP     query     ""oouu==ddbbaa,,ddcc==eexxaamm‐‐
       ppllee,,ddcc==ccoomm????oonnee??((uusseerr==bboobb))"". mmoonnggoodd executes  this  query  against  the
       LDAP server, returning the result ""ccnn==bboobb,,oouu==ddbbaa,,ddcc==eexxaammppllee,,ddcc==ccoomm"".

              If _-_-_l_d_a_p_U_s_e_r_T_o_D_N_M_a_p_p_i_n_g is unset, mmoonnggoodd applies no transforma‐
              tions to the username when attempting to authenticate or  autho‐
              rize a user against the LDAP server.

              This  setting  can  be  configured on a running mmoonnggoodd using the
              sseettPPaarraammeetteerr database command.

       ----llddaappAAuutthhzzQQuueerryyTTeemmppllaattee <<ssttrriinngg>>
              New in version 3.4: Available in MongoDB Enterprise only.

              A relative LDAP query URL formatted conforming  to  _R_F_C_4_5_1_5  and
              _R_F_C_4_5_1_6  that mmoonnggoodd executes to obtain the LDAP groups to which
              the authenticated user belongs to. The query is relative to  the
              host or hosts specified in _-_-_l_d_a_p_S_e_r_v_e_r_s.

              Use  the {{UUSSEERR}} placeholder in the URL to substitute the authen‐
              ticated username, or the transformed username if a _u_s_e_r_n_a_m_e _m_a_p_‐
              _p_i_n_g is specified.

              When  constructing  the query URL, ensure that the order of LDAP
              parameters respects RFC4516:

                 [ dn  [ ? [attributes] [ ? [scope] [ ? [filter] [ ? [Extensions] ] ] ] ] ]

              If your query includes an attribute,  mmoonnggoodd  assumes  that  the
              query retrieves a the DNs which this entity is member of.

              If  your query does not include an attribute, mmoonnggoodd assumes the
              query retrieves all entities which the user is member of.

              For each LDAP DN returned  by  the  query,  mmoonnggoodd  assigns  the
              authorized user a corresponding role on the aaddmmiinn database. If a
              role on the on the aaddmmiinn database exactly matches the DN, mmoonnggoodd
              grants  the user the roles and privileges assigned to that role.
              See the ddbb..ccrreeaatteeRRoollee(()) method for more information on  creating
              roles.

   EExxaammppllee
       This  LDAP  query  returns  any groups listed in the LDAP user object's
       mmeemmbbeerrOOff attribute.

          "{USER}?memberOf?base"

       Your LDAP configuration may not include the mmeemmbbeerrOOff attribute as  part
       of  the  user  schema,  may possess a different attribute for reporting
       group membership, or may not track group membership through attributes.
       Configure  your  query  with respect to your own unique LDAP configura‐
       tion.

              If unset, mmoonnggoodd cannot authorize users using LDAP.

              This setting can be configured on a  running  mmoonnggoodd  using  the
              sseettPPaarraammeetteerr database command.

              NNOOTTEE::
                 An  explanation of _R_F_C_4_5_1_5, _R_F_C_4_5_1_6 or LDAP queries is out of
                 scope for the MongoDB Documentation. Please  review  the  RFC
                 directly or use your preferred LDAP resource.

