       ----ooppllooggSSiizzee <<vvaalluuee>>
              Specifies a maximum size in megabytes for the replication opera‐
              tion log (i.e., the oplog).

              NNOOTTEE::
                 Starting  in MongoDB 4.0, the oplog can grow past its config‐
                 ured size limit to avoid deleting the mmaajjoorriittyy ccoommmmiitt ppooiinntt.

              By default, the mmoonnggoodd process creates an  oplog  based  on  the
              maximum amount of space available. For 64-bit systems, the oplog
              is typically 5% of available disk space.

              Once the mmoonnggoodd has created the oplog for the first time, chang‐
              ing  the  _-_-_o_p_l_o_g_S_i_z_e  option  will  not  affect the size of the
              oplog.

              To change the oplog size of a running replica  set  member,  use
              the  rreeppllSSeettRReessiizzeeOOpplloogg administrative command.  rreeppllSSeettRReessiizzeeOO‐‐
              pplloogg  enables  you  to  resize  the  oplog  dynamically  without
              restarting the _m_o_n_g_o_d process.

              See replica-set-oplog-sizing for more information.

       ----rreeppllIInnddeexxPPrreeffeettcchh
              _D_e_f_a_u_l_t: all

                 Storage Engine Specific Feature

                        _-_-_r_e_p_l_I_n_d_e_x_P_r_e_f_e_t_c_h  is only available with the mmmmaappvv11
                        storage engine.

              Determines which indexes secondary members of a replica set load
              into  memory  before  applying  operations  from  the  oplog. By
              default secondaries load all indexes  related  to  an  operation
              into memory before applying operations from the oplog.

              Set this option to one of the following:

                          ┌─────────┬────────────────────────────┐
                          │Value    │ Description                │
                          ├─────────┼────────────────────────────┤
                          │nnoonnee     │ Secondaries  do  not  load │
                          │         │ indexes into memory.       │
                          ├─────────┼────────────────────────────┤
                          │aallll      │ Secondaries    load    all │
                          │         │ indexes   related   to  an │
                          │         │ operation.                 │
                          ├─────────┼────────────────────────────┤
                          │__iidd__oonnllyy │ Secondaries load no  addi‐ │
                          │         │ tional indexes into memory │
